HW1 - Data Scraping & Taste of Data Analysis¶

Data Science in Korea University¶

COSE471, Spring 2015¶

Due : 3/30 (MON) 11:59 PM¶

Fetching population data from Wikipedia¶

In this example we will fetch data about countries and their population from Wikipedia.

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_past_and_future_population has several tables for individual countries, subcontinents as well as different years.

We will go through the following steps:¶

  • fetching html with embedded data
  • parsing html to extract the data
  • collecting the data in a panda dataframe
  • displaying the data

To give you some starting points for your homework, we will also show the different sub-steps that can be taken to reach the presented solution.

In [26]:
# special IPython command to prepare the notebook for matplotlib
%matplotlib inline 

from collections import defaultdict

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import requests
from pattern import web
from BeautifulSoup import BeautifulSoup

0. Fetching the Wikipedia site¶

Use requests library¶
In [27]:
url = 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_past_and_future_population'

# write your code here
website_html = requests.get(url).text

</div>
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">List of countries by past and future population</h1>
						<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
									<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>This article shows the (absolute) population of nearly all the political countries and dependencies in the world from 1950 to 2050. This one-century timespan provides a broad perspective on <a href="/wiki/Demography" title="Demography">demographic</a> change across the globe. According to these estimates, it can be seen that the <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">United States</a> surpassed the combined population of the fifteen republics of the former <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">Soviet Union</a> around the year 2003, and that by 2025 <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a> is projected to overtake <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a> as the world's most populous country.</p>
<p></p>

<p></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Introduction">Introduction</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_countries_by_past_and_future_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Introduction">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The starting year of 1950 is convenient, as it shows the world population growing and recovering from the <i>great demographic bleeding</i> of <a href="/wiki/World_War_II_casualties" title="World War II casualties">some 50-70 million deaths</a>, that had mainly taken place in the <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Front_(World_War_II)" title="Eastern Front (World War II)">Eastern Front</a> of <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>.</p>
<p>The figures shown here have been entirely taken (and processed) from the International Data Base (IDB) Division of the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Census_Bureau" title="United States Census Bureau">United States Census Bureau</a>. Every individual value has been automatically rounded to the nearest thousand, to assure data coherence, particularly when adding up (sub)totals. Although data from specific statistical offices may be more accurate, the information provided here has the advantage of being homogeneous.</p>
<p>Population estimates, <i>as long as they are based on recent censuses</i>, can be more easily projected into the <i>near</i> future than many <a href="/wiki/Macroeconomics" title="Macroeconomics">macroeconomic</a> indicators, such as <a href="/wiki/GDP" title="GDP" class="mw-redirect">GDPs</a>, which are much more sensitive to political and/or economic crises. This means that it is more accurate to make <a href="/wiki/Demographics" title="Demographics" class="mw-redirect">demographic</a> estimates for the next five (or even ten) years than trying to calculate the probable evolution of a GDP through the same time period (besides, in this latter case, deflacting has to be taken into account to compensate or make up for the distortion caused by <a href="/wiki/Inflation" title="Inflation">inflation</a>).</p>
<p>However, no projected population figures can be considered exact. In the IDB's particular case, <b>figures beyond the years 2020-2025 should be taken with caution</b>, as the <i>census way towards those years has yet to be paved</i>. Thus, from a present-day point of view, it is as if a <a href="/wiki/Demography" title="Demography">demographer</a> was looking through a kind of <i>cloudy glass</i> <sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> or <i>misty window</i>, and more or less precise “<a href="/wiki/Guesstimate" title="Guesstimate">guesstimates</a>” are the only <i>realistic</i> present-day available possibilities.</p>
<p>To make things more complicated, not all countries carry out censuses on a regular basis, especially some of the poorer, faster-growing <a href="/wiki/Sub-Saharan" title="Sub-Saharan" class="mw-redirect">sub-Saharan</a> African nations (whose evolution may be more interesting, from a <a href="/wiki/Demography" title="Demography">demographer</a>'s point of view, than the <i>stagnated</i> populations of countries like <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a> or <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italy</a>). For instance, it is difficult to know <i>real</i> present-day size of the population of <a href="/wiki/Angola" title="Angola">Angola</a>, as that country has not held a census since 1970 (prior to its post-colonial civil war, that broke out in 1975, with its toll of dead people and refugees). As it is widely known in the world of <a href="/wiki/Demographics" title="Demographics" class="mw-redirect">demographics</a> (from historical empirical data), countries like those (along with other nations like <a href="/wiki/Algeria" title="Algeria">Algeria</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bangladesh" title="Bangladesh">Bangladesh</a>, <a href="/wiki/Egypt" title="Egypt">Egypt</a>, <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">India</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Pakistan" title="Pakistan">Pakistan</a>) -with their low <a href="/wiki/Family_planning" title="Family planning">family planning</a>- tend to grow much faster than the <a href="/wiki/Population_ageing" title="Population ageing">aging</a> <a href="/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">European</a> nations or <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a>. In general, although the former countries may slow down their respective demographic growths rates in the decades to come, it is unlikely that they will stabilize their respective populations by 2050, as predicted by the IDB data in some cases; they may also stay near the relatively high average level of 1.5% increase per year. Something similar can be said about <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a>, whose population is still growing at an absolute rate of <i>some 10 million additional inhabitants per year</i>, despite its government’s efforts to stabilize it, through its <a href="/wiki/One-child_policy" title="One-child policy">one child per couple policy</a>.</p>
<p>On the other hand, some other countries, like the small <a href="/wiki/Asia" title="Asia">Asian</a> State of <a href="/wiki/Bhutan" title="Bhutan">Bhutan</a>, have only recently had a <i>thorough</i> census for the first time: In Bhutan's case in particular, before its national 2005 population survey,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> the IDB showed an estimated 2+ million figure, which was silently reduced in a drastic way, after the new census results were finally included in its <a href="/wiki/Database" title="Database">database</a>.</p>
<p>Besides, the IDB usually takes some time before including new data, as it happened in the case of Indonesia. That is why that country was reported by the IDB to have an <i>inflated</i> population of some 242 million by mid-2005, because it had not still processed the final results of the eventually <i>moderate</i> 2000 Indonesian census.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> A similar discrepancy has also occurred with the relatively recent <a href="/wiki/Ethiopia" title="Ethiopia">Ethiopian</a> 2007 census,<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup> that resulted in "only" 73,918,505 inhabitants (preliminary figure).</p>
<p>The largest absolute potential discrepancies are naturally related to the most populous nations. However, smaller states, such as <a href="/wiki/Tuvalu" title="Tuvalu">Tuvalu</a>, can have large <i>relative</i> discrepancies. For instance, the 2002 census in that <a href="/wiki/Oceania" title="Oceania">Oceanian</a> island, which gave a final population of 9,561<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup> shows that IDB estimates can be significantly off.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Preliminary_notes">Preliminary notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_countries_by_past_and_future_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Preliminary notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>The national <b>1 July, mid-year population estimates</b> (usually based on past national censuses) supplied in these tables are given in <b>thousands</b>.</p>
<p>The table columns can be <b>sorted</b> by clicking on their respective heading.</p>
<p>The retrospective figures assume the present-day names and world political division, for instance, providing data for each of the 15 republics of the former <a href="/wiki/Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union">Soviet Union</a>, as if they had already been independent by 1950, and not since the end of 1991, as they really are. An inverse criterion corresponds to <a href="/wiki/Germany" title="Germany">Germany</a>, forcefully divided since the end of the <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">Second World War</a> and eventually <a href="/wiki/Reunification_of_Germany" title="Reunification of Germany" class="mw-redirect">reunified</a> since October 3, 1990.</p>
<p>Other issues concerning some countries or territories are the following ones:</p>
<ul>
<li><span class="flagicon"><a href="/wiki/Burma" title="Burma"><img alt="Burma" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Flag_of_Myanmar.svg/23px-Flag_of_Myanmar.svg.png" width="23" height="15" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Flag_of_Myanmar.svg/35px-Flag_of_Myanmar.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Flag_of_Myanmar.svg/45px-Flag_of_Myanmar.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1800" data-file-height="1200" /></a></span> Burma is the <a href="/wiki/Names_of_Burma" title="Names of Burma">traditional English name for (the Union of) Myanmar</a>, as used by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Census_Bureau" title="United States Census Bureau">United States Census Bureau</a>.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><span class="flagicon"><a href="/wiki/Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo" title="Democratic Republic of the Congo"><img alt="Democratic Republic of the Congo" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Flag_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo.svg/20px-Flag_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo.svg.png" width="20" height="15" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Flag_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo.svg/31px-Flag_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6f/Flag_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo.svg/40px-Flag_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="600" /></a></span> The Democratic Republic of the Congo, formerly known as Zaire from 1971 to 1997, is referred to as <a href="/wiki/Congo_(Kinshasa)" title="Congo (Kinshasa)" class="mw-redirect">Congo (Kinshasa)</a> in the IDB database (to differentiate it from the <a href="/wiki/Republic_of_the_Congo" title="Republic of the Congo">Republic of the Congo</a> whose capital is the city of <a href="/wiki/Brazzaville" title="Brazzaville">Brazzaville</a>).</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><span class="flagicon"><a href="/wiki/France" title="France"><img alt="France" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Flag_of_France.svg/23px-Flag_of_France.svg.png" width="23" height="15" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Flag_of_France.svg/35px-Flag_of_France.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Flag_of_France.svg/45px-Flag_of_France.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="900" data-file-height="600" /></a></span> The population figures for <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a> includes the four <a href="/wiki/Overseas_departments_and_territories_of_France" title="Overseas departments and territories of France">overseas departments</a> of <a href="/wiki/French_Guiana" title="French Guiana">French Guiana</a>, <a href="/wiki/Guadeloupe" title="Guadeloupe">Guadeloupe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Martinique" title="Martinique">Martinique</a> and <a href="/wiki/R%C3%A9union" title="Réunion">Réunion</a>, but excludes <a href="/wiki/Saint_Barth%C3%A9lemy" title="Saint Barthélemy">Saint Barthélemy</a> and the French part of <a href="/wiki/Saint_Martin_(France)" title="Saint Martin (France)" class="mw-redirect">Saint Martin</a>, which split from Guadeloupe in 2007.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><span class="flagicon"><a href="/wiki/Hong_Kong" title="Hong Kong"><img alt="Hong Kong" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Flag_of_Hong_Kong.svg/23px-Flag_of_Hong_Kong.svg.png" width="23" height="15" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Flag_of_Hong_Kong.svg/35px-Flag_of_Hong_Kong.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5b/Flag_of_Hong_Kong.svg/45px-Flag_of_Hong_Kong.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="900" data-file-height="600" /></a></span> <span class="flagicon"><a href="/wiki/Macau" title="Macau"><img alt="Macau" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Flag_of_Macau.svg/23px-Flag_of_Macau.svg.png" width="23" height="15" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Flag_of_Macau.svg/35px-Flag_of_Macau.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Flag_of_Macau.svg/45px-Flag_of_Macau.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="660" data-file-height="440" /></a></span> The former <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">British</a> colony of <a href="/wiki/Hong_Kong" title="Hong Kong">Hong Kong</a> and former <a href="/wiki/Portugal" title="Portugal">Portuguese</a> colony of <a href="/wiki/Macau" title="Macau">Macau</a> continue to have their own figures, even though they were returned to <a href="/wiki/People%27s_Republic_of_China" title="People's Republic of China" class="mw-redirect">Chinese</a> sovereignty in 1997 and 1999 respectively. The Chinese government considers both present-day Special Administrative Regions (SARs) as separate entities from a statistical point of view, and their censuses are still carried out on different dates from the ones in mainland China.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><span class="flagicon"><a href="/wiki/Montserrat" title="Montserrat"><img alt="Montserrat" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Flag_of_Montserrat.svg/23px-Flag_of_Montserrat.svg.png" width="23" height="12" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Flag_of_Montserrat.svg/35px-Flag_of_Montserrat.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Flag_of_Montserrat.svg/46px-Flag_of_Montserrat.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1200" data-file-height="600" /></a></span> About half the population of the <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">British</a> <a href="/wiki/Caribbean" title="Caribbean">Caribbean</a> colony of <a href="/wiki/Montserrat" title="Montserrat">Montserrat</a> (within the <a href="/wiki/Lesser_Antilles" title="Lesser Antilles">Lesser Antilles</a>) was evacuated in 1995, following a <a href="/wiki/Volcanic_eruption" title="Volcanic eruption" class="mw-redirect">volcanic eruption</a> that severely damaged its capital, the town of <a href="/wiki/Plymouth,_Montserrat" title="Plymouth, Montserrat">Plymouth</a>.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><span class="flagicon"><a href="/wiki/State_of_Palestine" title="State of Palestine"><img alt="State of Palestine" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Flag_of_Palestine.svg/23px-Flag_of_Palestine.svg.png" width="23" height="12" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Flag_of_Palestine.svg/35px-Flag_of_Palestine.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Flag_of_Palestine.svg/46px-Flag_of_Palestine.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1200" data-file-height="600" /></a></span> Although no figures are given for the <a href="/wiki/Palestinian_territories" title="Palestinian territories">Palestinian territories</a> as a whole, data is supplied for both the <a href="/wiki/Gaza_strip" title="Gaza strip" class="mw-redirect">Gaza strip</a> and the <a href="/wiki/West_Bank" title="West Bank">West Bank</a>.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li><span class="flagicon"><a href="/wiki/Serbia" title="Serbia"><img alt="Serbia" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Flag_of_Serbia.svg/23px-Flag_of_Serbia.svg.png" width="23" height="15" class="thumbborder" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Flag_of_Serbia.svg/35px-Flag_of_Serbia.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/Flag_of_Serbia.svg/45px-Flag_of_Serbia.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="1350" data-file-height="900" /></a></span> The <a href="/wiki/Serbia" title="Serbia">Serbian</a> population refers only to that of the "residual" Yugoslav republic under that name, after secession of <a href="/wiki/Montenegro" title="Montenegro">Montenegro</a> <i>(Crna Gora)</i> and, more recently, <a href="/wiki/Kosovo" title="Kosovo">Kosovo</a> (the latter being recognized as an independent state by the <a href="/wiki/Federal_government_of_the_United_States" title="Federal government of the United States">United States government</a> on 18 February 2008, the <a href="/wiki/US_Census_Bureau" title="US Census Bureau" class="mw-redirect">US Census Bureau</a> reflects the resulting <a href="/wiki/Demography" title="Demography">demographic</a> change; nevertheless, many countries have not recognized this declaration of independence).</li>
</ul>
<p>Finally, the <a href="/wiki/Eastern_Europe" title="Eastern Europe">Eastern</a> and <a href="/wiki/Western_Europe" title="Western Europe">Western Europe</a> subtotals follow the former <a href="/wiki/Cold_War" title="Cold War">Cold War</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Iron_Curtain" title="Iron Curtain">Iron Curtain</a> division of Europe.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Formulas_used_to_calculate_demographic_growth">Formulas used to calculate demographic growth</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_countries_by_past_and_future_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Formulas used to calculate demographic growth">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>To the right of each year column (except for the initial 1950 one), a percentage figure is shown, corresponding to the <i>average annual</i> growth for each previous five-year period. Thus, the figures after the 1960 column calculates the percentage for the 1955-60 period, the ones after the 1980 one, the value for 1975-80, and so on.</p>
<p>The formulas used to carry out these last calculations, are the standard ones, used both by the <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> Statistics Division and by National Census Offices worldwide. They correspond to the <a href="/wiki/Exponential_function" title="Exponential function">exponential</a> geometrical growth, and have the following general form: <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\left ( \sqrt[y_f-y_i]{\frac{p_f}{p_i}} -1 \right ) \times 100" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/3/5/c35437ff6270d1cf1cb4042d2ec665eb.png" />, where <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="p_i" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/a/4/8a4bbd153c74655abb7ca04c0fa901d8.png" /> and <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="p_f" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/a/2/1a2ae1978c4f7a32d6d8841c1144771c.png" /> stand for the initial and final population, respectively, within a stated time period. The same criteria applies to <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="y_i" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/8/d/18daef71b5d25ce76b8628a81e4fc76b.png" /> and <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="y_f" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/e/d/5ede52281790304b3c3bee944c57b903.png" />, the two variables indicating the two years involved. In terms of <a href="/wiki/Logarithm" title="Logarithm">natural logarithms</a>, both formulas can be expressed as follows: <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\left ( e^{\frac{ln(p_f / p_i)}{(y_f - y_i)}} - 1 \right ) \times 100" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/f/7/af7a871f34351b5cba371c0e108f93fe.png" />. For the practical purposes of the calculations shown here, where five-year periods are involved, we can simplify the formulas, leaving them like this: <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\left ( \sqrt[5]{\frac{p_f}{p_i}} -1 \right ) \times 100" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/5/1/f51662bebc2ebfbf9b6be2b8fb2369c9.png" /> and <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\left (e^{\frac{ln(p_f/p_i)}{5}}-1 \right ) \times 100" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/5/3/953cc3afd218f7c641ad9a2372d1cb30.png" /></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Sources">Sources</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_countries_by_past_and_future_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Sources">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.census.gov/ipc/www/idb/informationGateway.php">United States Census Bureau - International Data Base (IDB)</a>, retrieved on 10 January 2012, including the minor <a href="/wiki/Demography" title="Demography">demographic</a> corrections from the June 2011 release notes. The <a href="/wiki/The_World_Factbook" title="The World Factbook">CIA World Factbook</a> is sometimes attributed as a source of these updated world population data; however, the CIA takes their demographic information from the IDB. The estimates are all for 1 July of each year mentioned.</p>
<p><br /></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="External_links">External links</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_countries_by_past_and_future_population&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: External links">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.citypopulation.de">City population</a> provides <a href="/wiki/Demography" title="Demography">demographic</a> data <i>not</i> only for cities, but also for countries (and their primary administrative divisions), sometimes going back to the 1980s.</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.geohive.com/earth/his_proj.aspx">GeoHive page</a> with historic, current and future population by country, also based on the United States Census Bureau International Data Base.</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.populstat.info">Population statistics</a> has a collection of <a href="/wiki/Demographics" title="Demographics" class="mw-redirect">demographic</a> statistics from every country and territory, some of them going back <i>centuries</i>.</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.statoids.com">Statoids</a> gives historical and present day census data about countries and territories, and figures for their first (and even second) level administrative divisions.</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://archive.is/20121204142112/http://www.world-gazetteer.com/">World gazetteer</a> includes present-day national population projections, going back to the 1990s in some cases.</li>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ifs.du.edu/ifs/Ifs.aspx">International Futures</a> (IFs) is an integrated global modeling system that forecasts demographic, economic, energy, agricultural, socio-political, and environmental subsystems for 183 countries interacting in the global system.</li>
</ul>

1. Parsing html data¶

Data that we are going to use is “tables” titled below:

  • Country and territory breakdown by past or historical (and consolidated) population, from 1950 to 1980
  • Country and territory breakdown by past or historical (and consolidated) population, from 1985 to 2015
  • Country and territory breakdown by past or historical (and consolidated) population, from 2020 to 2050
Use either Pattern or BeautifulSoup¶
In [28]:
def get_population_html_tables(html):
    """
    Parse html and 
    
    return: html tables of wikipedia population data.
    """
    
    dom = web.Element(html)    #pattern.web method Element

    #step1: look at html source!"
    
    #step2: get all tables"
    #tbls = dom('table')
    #step3: get all tables we care about"
    tbls = dom.by_class('sortable wikitable') # return a list of Elements
    return tbls

tables = get_population_html_tables(website_html) # list of Elements with

    # 2nd try

    # 3rd try
    return tbl('th')[0].content

# write your code here
def get_countries_population(tables):
    """
    tables: list of dom Elements
    Extract population data for countries from all tables and 
    store it in dictionary.
    """
    result = defaultdict(dict)
        # 1. step: try to extract data for a single table
    for tbl in tables:    
        #tbl = tables[0]    # dom
        headers = tbl('tr')    # list
        first_header = headers[0]   # dom
        th_s = first_header('th')    # list

        years = [int(val.content) for val in th_s if val.content.isnumeric()]
        year_indices = [idx for idx, val in enumerate(th_s) if val.content.isnumeric()]
        print years
        print year_indices

        # 2. step: iterate over all tables, extract headings and actual data and combine data into single dict
        rows = tbl('tr')[1:]
        for row in rows:
            tds = row('td')    # list of td doms
            country_name = tds[0]('a')[0].content
            population_by_year = [int(tds[colidx].content.replace(',',''))
                                  for colidx in year_indices]
            subdict = dict(zip(years, population_by_year))    # dict, key = years, vals = population
            result[country_name].update(subdict)
    return result
    
result = get_countries_population(tables_by_type['Country or territory'])
print len(result), "Countries extracted"
print result['Canada']
print hash(1985), hash(2050)

4-2. Plot 5 most populous countries from 2010 and 2060¶

In [34]:
def plot_populous(df, year):
    # sort table depending on data value in year column
    df_by_year = df.sort(year, ascending=False)
    
    plt.figure()
    for i in range(5):
        row = df_by_year.ix[i]
        plt.plot(row.index, row, label=row.name)
        
    plt.ylim(ymin=0) # start y axis at 0

    plt.xticks(rotation=70)    # x values tilted
    plt.legend(loc='best')    # line label
    plt.xlabel("Year")
    plt.ylabel("# people (million)")
    plt.title("Most populous countries in %d" % year)
    
plot_populous(df, 2010)
plot_populous(df, 2050)

## 1. organize data

# yearly growth = (year(n) - year(n-5))/year(n-5)
# year(n)
skorea_2010_2050 = df[[2010,2015,2020,2025,2030,2035,2040,2045,2050]].ix['South Korea']

# year(n-5)
skorea_2005_2045 = df[[2005,2010,2015,2020,2025,2030,2035,2040,2045]].ix['South Korea']
skorea_2005_2045 = skorea_2005_2045.rename(index = {i:i+5 for i in skorea_2005_2045.index})
# year(n) - year(n-5)
skorea_difference = (skorea_2010_2050 - skorea_2005_2045)

# (year(n) - year(n-5))/year(n-5)
skorea_growthrate = skorea_difference / skorea_2005_2045 * 100

## 2. population graph
plt.figure()
plt.plot(skorea_2010_2050.index, skorea_2010_2050, label = skorea_2010_2050.name)

plt.xticks(rotation=70)    # x values tilted
plt.legend(loc='best')    # line label
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("# people (million)")
plt.title("South Korea's population (2010 - 2050)")
plt.grid()


## 3. growth rate graph
plt.figure()
plt.plot(skorea_growthrate.index, skorea_growthrate, label = skorea_growthrate.name)

plt.xticks(rotation=70)    # x values tilted
plt.legend(loc='best')    # line label
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("%")
plt.title("South Korea's yearly growth rate in population (2010 - 2050)")
plt.grid()

## 1.1 get oecd name list
url_OECD = 'http://oecd.org/about/membersandpartners/list-oecd-member-countries.htm'

def get_OECD_list(url):
    content = requests.get(url).text

    dom = web.Element(content)    #pattern.web method Element
    table = dom("table")[1]('td')

    countries = []
    for i in table:
        if i.by_class("&amp;amp;quot;more&amp;amp;quot;") != []:
            countries.append(i[0])

    names = []
    for c in countries[:-1]:
        names.append(titlecase(str(c.content).lower()))
        
    return names

## 1.2 make some adjustments on differences in names
oecd = get_OECD_list(url_OECD)
oecd.remove('Korea')
oecd.append('South Korea')
oecd.remove('Slovak Republic')
oecd.append('Slovakia')

## 2. from dataframe, extract records of oecd countries
growth_oecd = growth_unsorted_df.loc[[c for c in oecd],:].sort('growth rate between 2010 and 2050', ascending=False)
print growth_oecd


## 3. bar chart on grwoth rates
growth_oecd.plot(kind='bar')

5-4. Your Analysis Report (Either Korean or English)¶

1. 한국의 인구 증감/증감율 예측 (2010 - 2050)¶

- 인구 증감율 그래프 조사 방법: 5년 단위로 인구 증감율 측정
예) 2015년 인구 증감율(%) = {(2015년 인구 증감)/2010년 인구} * 100 = {(2015년 인구 - 2010년 인구)/2010년 인구} * 100

- 한국의 인구는 2025년을 기점으로 하락하며, 그 하락률이 점차 증가하는 양상을 보인다. 한국 인구 감소의 원인은 저출산과 고령화다. 여성의 사회 진출과 양육비용의 지속적 증가로 자녀를 적게 낳거나 낳지 않는 사람이 늘어나고, 베이비붐 세대의 고령화로 인해 고령 인구 비율이 점점 높아지고 있기 때문이다. 

참고: http://magazine.hankyung.com/business/apps/news?popup=0&nid=01&nkey=2014011600946000211&mode=sub_view

2. 전세계 인구 증감율 히스토그램 (2010년 대비 2050년 증감율) & 최고 인구 증감율 국가 인구 그래프¶

- 히스토그램 조사 방법: 인구 증감율(%) = {(2050년 인구 - 2010년 인구)/2010년 인구} * 100

- 전세계 국가들의 2010년 대비 2050년 인구 증감율로 히스토그램을 만들었을 때 대략 5 개의 아웃라이어를 발견할 수 있다. 인구 증가율이 가장 가파른 이들 다섯 개 국가는 그 다음 그래프에서 보듯이, Uganda, Niger, Ethiopia, Burkina Faso, Zambia로 모두 아프리카 국가들이다. 이처럼 아프리카 국가들의 인구증가율이 가장 가파른 까닭은 지속적으로 높은 출산율과 성공적인 에이즈 퇴치 노력 때문이다. 대부분의 아프리카 국가의 출산율은 5명 정도이며, Niger의 경우에는 무려 7명에 이른다. 또한 에이즈 퇴치 노력으로 사망자수가 준 것도 영향을 끼쳤다. 

참고: http://www.economist.com/blogs/graphicdetail/2013/06/daily-chart-10
     http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/656619.html

3. OECD 인구 증감율 막대 그래프 (2010년 대비 2050년 증감율)¶

- 인구 증감율 막대 그래프 조사 방법: 인구 증감율(%) = {(2050년 인구 - 2010년 인구)/2010년 인구} * 100

- 룩셈부르크의 인구 증감율이 OECD 국가 중 가장 높은 것으로 나타나는데, 룩셈부르크는 인구가 작아 적극적인 이민 정책을 실시하기 때문으로 볼 수 있다. 룩셈부르크는 이민자에게도 공직을 개방하고 투표권을 부여한다. 현재 35퍼센트의 인구가 이민자로 이루어져 있다. 이러한 적극적인 이민 정책은 룩셈부르크의 미래 인구 증가에 긍정적 영향을 미치는 것으로 보인다. 

참고: http://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/economies/Europe/Luxembourg.html
